{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "On the other hand, hybrid recommendation approaches can enhance recommendation quality and address the primary limitations of traditional approaches.",
    "Most hybrid recommendation approaches involve combining CF with other recommendation approaches [2,3,5,6].The quality of recommendations heavily relies on the similarity measures used to compare items or users.",
    "With respect to early recommendation techniques, similarity measures primarily relied on examining the content descriptions and user profiles, often ignoring to consider meaningful aspects that had the potential to greatly improve the accuracy of recommendations [6][7][8][9][10].In recent recommendation research works, the incorporation of semantic enhancement based on semantic similarity has received increasing attention, with research findings showing promising results [4,[11][12][13][14][15].",
    "Semanticenhanced recommendation techniques have the potential to provide more accurate recommendations by integrating semantic information from user and/or item profiles into the recommendation process.",
    "These techniques mainly utilize Semantic Web technologies, including ontologies and semantic reasoning, to improve the similarity assessments used in traditional CB and CF approaches.To address the gap between early and recent recommendation research, four primary hybridization techniques can be identified: (i) augmenting domain knowledge represented in ontologies with item-based CF to enhance similarity estimations [14,16], (ii) enhancing the conventional user-based CF approach by incorporating semantic information from ontologies [17][18][19][20], (iii) combining user-based and/or item-based CF with semantic-enhanced Content-Based filtering [9,13,21], and (iv) integrating semantic user-based and/or itembased CF with semantic-enhanced CB filtering [12,22].Through an extensive literature review, it was observed that existing semantic similarity measures employed to enhance CF recommendations primarily rely on direct hierarchical (i.e., taxonomical) relationships among items and their semantic descriptions, as defined by ontological data type and object properties."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Most hybrid recommendation approaches involve combining CF with other recommendation approaches [2,3,5,6].The quality of recommendations heavily relies on the similarity measures used to compare items or users.",
    "With respect to early recommendation techniques, similarity measures primarily relied on examining the content descriptions and user profiles, often ignoring to consider meaningful aspects that had the potential to greatly improve the accuracy of recommendations [6][7][8][9][10].In recent recommendation research works, the incorporation of semantic enhancement based on semantic similarity has received increasing attention, with research findings showing promising results [4,[11][12][13][14][15].",
    "These techniques mainly utilize Semantic Web technologies, including ontologies and semantic reasoning, to improve the similarity assessments used in traditional CB and CF approaches.To address the gap between early and recent recommendation research, four primary hybridization techniques can be identified: (i) augmenting domain knowledge represented in ontologies with item-based CF to enhance similarity estimations [14,16], (ii) enhancing the conventional user-based CF approach by incorporating semantic information from ontologies [17][18][19][20], (iii) combining user-based and/or item-based CF with semantic-enhanced Content-Based filtering [9,13,21], and (iv) integrating semantic user-based and/or itembased CF with semantic-enhanced CB filtering [12,22].Through an extensive literature review, it was observed that existing semantic similarity measures employed to enhance CF recommendations primarily rely on direct hierarchical (i.e., taxonomical) relationships among items and their semantic descriptions, as defined by ontological data type and object properties."
